  p.lead.question
    | Help! I’m completely out of water! What can I do to get it back on?
  p
    |
      First thing you can do, before you call anyone, is to reset the breaker.
      Even if it doesn’t looked tripped, it can be disengaged enough to break
      the circuit. If you don’t know which breaker is it, you can simply reset
      them all (as well as your clocks).
  p

    |
      If the breaker isn’t at fault, you should call us so we can walk you
      through a couple other possibilities.  However, we do not encourage you to
      open electrical boxes on your own and tinker with the parts. The risk of
      electrocution is too great if you are unfamiliar or uncomfortable with
      them.

  p.lead.question
    | I’m considering a filtration system, but I’m not sure I need it.
    | How can I be sure?
  p
    |
      There are four major facets of water quality that you should evaluate
      before buying a system from anyone: Color, Smell, Taste, and
      Contamination.
  p
    |
      To test for contamination, simply contact the health department for the
      county you live in and request a Bacteriological test (there will be a
      small fee). This test looks for the presence of bacteria, specifically
      coliform bacteria (it is sometimes called a coliform test). Wells that
      test positive should have a chlorination system installed to prevent
      illness. Other tests for lead and other chemicals are also available, for
      additional peace of mind.
  p
    |
      Testing for color, smell and taste is much easier. Simply pour your water
      in a large, clean and clear glass container and evaluate it using your
      senses. Place a sheet of blank computer paper behind the glass to evaluate
      the color, and use hot water when checking for odor (hot water amplifies
      odor). Look for sediment that falls to the bottom of the glass, and check
      your fixtures for scale or rust stains. Then if you still aren’t sure...

  p.lead.question
    | What kinds of tests are there to evaluate water, and can I
    | trust the results?
  p
    |
      Mosts tests and kits are extremely reliable and simple, especially if you
      are doing it yourself and can duplicate the results over two or three
      testings. However, there have been reports in the past of companies
      employing methods that are misleading, especially when a sale depends on
      it. Nowadays, there is little reason for a homeowner or business owner to
      rely on a salesman to do their water testing, because test kits are cheap
      and readily available on the internet. We use a very simple kit that
      evaluates PH, Hardness and Dissolved Iron in minutes. It is nearly
      identical to a test strip kit you would use to check a pool for PH and
      chlorine content.

